more_like_this.title: The International Owl Center headquarters in the small city of Houston in southeastern Minnesota. The wildlife center, created in 1996, is dedicated to the study and promotion of the species of birds that proliferate along the nearby Root River Trail. City employee Karla Bloem founded the organization with an eye to the success of the National Eagle Center just one hour north in Wabasha, Minnesota

more_like_this.title: Thomas Miller's 1987 "Winter Warrior" sculpture outside the Blue Earth County Library in Mankato, Minnesota. It, and the county's Reconciliation Memorial across the street, keep before the public the story of the largest mass execution in U.S. history when 38 Dakota Indians were hanged here by the government during the U.S.-Dakota Conflict of 1862

description: Gordie Keenan was born in 1954, in Norfolk, Virginia. He was educated in Rochester, New York, and later attended the State University of New York Maritime College. He moved to Houston in 1991 and has worked for Higman Marine Services, Inc. since 2005, where he was asked to run the personnel side of the business. Keenan describes his maritime career working different roles at Exxon and in several privately-owned towboat companies. He provides insight into ways the towboat industry has reformed itself to become more professional over the last few decades. This interview was accompanied by two photographs of employees: Douglas Dunn, pilot (with Gordie Keenan); Randall Spann, steersman; and Sean McDonald, steersman, of Higman Marine Services, Inc.

description: A team of musicians and community scholars from the Chicano music community created documentation of the contemporary scene in Houston. This scene is influenced by a mix of gulf coast African American and Cajun-inflected blues and R&B musical traditions as well as the country, Orquesta and Conjunto music often associated with more prominent Chicano music scenes in South and Central Texas. The team conducted interviews with musicians, dance hall owners, producers, fans and others, culminating with a street party community documentation/archives event featuring group discussions, story booths, photo sharing and duplication opportunities and music performance.

description: Collection of audio oral history interviews documenting the diverse culture of workers associated with the Port of Houston, Texas, and the Houston Ship Channel. Interviews were conducted from July 2010 to October 2012 by Pat Jasper, Director of the Houston Folklife and Traditional Arts Program at the Houston Arts Alliance; Carl Lindahl, Professor, Department of English, University of Houston;  Elizabeth "Betsy" Peterson; Harold L. Dodd; and Anthony Potoczniak. The interviews document the work life of longshoremen, pilots, dockworkers, railroad workers, admiralty attorneys, chaplains, port engineers, real estate agents, Coast Guard officers, and International Longshoremen's Association members and officers, and other harbor and shipyard workers at the Port of Houston. The collection includes interview logs, photographs, and related materials.
